[{"id":"VH976642","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">A population geneticist is conducting an investigation on a population of mice. The geneticist determines the genotypes for a particular trait of all of the mice in the population during generation&nbsp;1 and then removes all of the mice with the genotype <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"lower case a lower case a\"><math alttext=\"lower case a lower case a\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>a</mi><mi>a</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The remaining members of the population are allowed to randomly mate with one another to produce generation&nbsp;2 and future generations. A model of the investigation is shown in Figure&nbsp;1. Each of the fifteen genotypes shown in generation 1 and generation 2 represents 100 mice.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two circles labeled Generation 1 and Generation 2. Generation 1 contains the genotypes of fifteen individuals, which consist of nine upper case A upper case A genotypes, two upper case A lower case a genotypes, and four lower case a lower case a genotypes. Several arrows indicate the removal of the lower case a lower case a alleles from the Generation 1 population. An arrow labeled Random Mating points from Generation 1 to Generation 2. Generation 2 contains the genotypes of fifteen individuals, which consist of eleven upper case A upper case A genotypes and four upper case A lower case a genotypes.\" height=\"225\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH976642.g02.png\" width=\"500\" />\n<p class=\"caption\">Figure 1. Model of effect of selective mouse removal on a population</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following best illustrates the change in the frequencies of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-l